               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17671021-7-person95">
                  Robert 
                  Robinson 
               <interp inst="t17671021-7-person95" type="surname" value="Robinson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17671021-7-person95" type="given" value="Robert"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17671021-7-person95" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 23rd of September I had my watch at six in the afternoon, and the next morning I missed it, with my silver buckles; the prisoner was also missing from on board our ship in the river; I went in search of him, and found him; he confest he had taken them, and directed me where he had pawned the watch, and sold the buckles; I went and found the watch, and the buckles were knocked to pieces and melted down; I saw the brass chapes.</p>
               <p>Mr. Allen. The watch was pawned to me, by 
               <persName id="t17671021-7-person96">
                  Sarah 
                  Rawlins 
               <interp inst="t17671021-7-person96" type="surname" value="Rawlins"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17671021-7-person96" type="given" value="Sarah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17671021-7-person96" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; the prosecutor came and owned it, and I delivered it to him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17671021-7-person97">
                  Archibald 
                  Stranger 
               <interp inst="t17671021-7-person97" type="surname" value="Stranger"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17671021-7-person97" type="given" value="Archibald"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17671021-7-person97" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner and a bad woman were brought to me on the 26th of September,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="176710210006"></xptr> by a watchman; and on the Monday morning, the prosecutor came, and charged him with stealing his watch and buckles from on, board a ship; when we came before the magistrates, he confessed he had taken them, and went to a house No 2. in the back lane, where he said he had given the watch to a woman to pawn; she confessed she had pawned it, and had the duplicate; the prisoner said he had sold the buckles to a silversmith, they were an old pair; the silversmith said he had melted them down; we took the woman to the pawnbroker's, and the watch was delivered to us, (produced and deposed to by prosecutor.)</p>
